INSERT INTO wp_postmeta VALUES("642","159","section_2","<div class=\"col-sm-12 col-md-12\">\r\n<h2 class=\"heading\">Windows XP End Of Life Migration</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"ccol-sm-12 col-md-6\">\r\n<h3 class=\"lead\">Not just sales hype</h3>\r\nOn April 8, 2014 Microsoft will terminate its\' support for Windows XP. This isn\'t to be taken lightly by the IT community. Customers around the globe routinely download security patches, often distributed multiple times per week, to patch the aging Windows XP operating system.\r\n\r\nThese security updates don\'t just patch vulnerabilities used by virii, but also malicious scripting, malware, trojans, denial of service (DoS) and other attacks. When Microsoft stops creating the patches, it will likely take just days before another vulnerability is discovered. In the past these would have been patched, but now they will not - essentially announcing a free for all on every unsuspecting Windows XP user.\r\n\r\nMicrosoft will not offer continued support for the product without customized dedicated support contracts specifically for that purpose. Their own estimates suggest that companies wishing to pursue this route budget an estimated minimum of at least $200,000 for that contract. You will likely be on your own, and the hackers know it.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-sm-12 col-md-6\">\r\n<h3 class=\"lead\">Why is it worth upgrading to Windows 7/8?</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li class=\"well\">\r\n<h4>Increased Core Security</h4>\r\nIncreased core operating system security. Various aspects of the operating system have been modified to make it more difficult for applications to run without permission, as well as modifing files on the system without the users\' knowledge.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"well\">\r\n<h4>Network Control</h4>\r\nNetwork control over machine level detail via Group Policy Objects (GPO) has been vastly expanded. You can control more things, to a finer level of detail, than you could with either Windows XP or Windows Vista.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"well\">\r\n<h4>Complete Support</h4>\r\nMore complete and standard support for today\'s newer architecture machines. Multi-core and multi-socket machines are handled with a more advanced thread manager, allowing more performance to be achieved with existing hardware. Newer hardware takes this advantage even further with support for SSD/USB swap drives, virtualized component utilization and other features simply not available in Windows XP.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"well\">\r\n<h4>Windows Server Integration</h4>\r\nMore direct and tightly integrated control with Windows Server 2008/2011 SBS/2012. If you have a Windows Server 2003 architecture, your Windows 7 clients will work without issue. But if you have any of the next generation Windows Server products you\'ll find additional control and configuration options available on the Windows 7/8 machines that can aid in creating a more standardized and more easily managed IT infrastructure. From deployment options to product update managment, administering Windows 7/8 boxes is just easier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe invite you to read <a title=\"Ten Things You Should Know About Windows 7 vs. Windows XP\" href=\"http://www.novastar.net/gk-231015.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Ten Things You Should Know About Windows 7 vs. Windows XP</a> by Global Knowledge® to get a detailed analysis on the differences between Windows XP and Windows 7.\r\n\r\n</div>");
