INSERT INTO wp_postmeta VALUES("666","162","section_2","<div class=\"col-sm-12 col-md-12\">\r\n<h2 class=\"heading\">Windows XP End Of Life Migration</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"ccol-sm-12 col-md-6\">\r\n<h3 class=\"lead\">Not just sales hype</h3>\r\nOn April 8, 2014 Microsoft will terminate its\' support for Windows XP. This isn\'t to be taken lightly by the IT community. Customers around the globe routinely download security patches, often distributed multiple times per week, to patch the aging Windows XP operating system.\r\n\r\nThese security updates don\'t just patch vulnerabilities used by virii, but also malicious scripting, malware, trojans, denial of service (DoS) and other attacks. When Microsoft stops creating the patches, it will likely take just days before another vulnerability is discovered. In the past these would have been patched, but now they will not - essentially announcing a free for all on every unsuspecting Windows XP user.\r\n\r\nMicrosoft will not offer continued support for the product without customized dedicated support contracts specifically for that purpose. Their own estimates suggest that companies wishing to pursue this route budget an estimated minimum of at least $200,000 for that contract. You will likely be on your own, and the hackers know it.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-sm-12 col-md-6\">\r\n<h3 class=\"lead\">Why is it worth upgrading to Windows 7/8?</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li class=\"well\">\r\n<h4>Increased Core Security</h4>\r\nIncreased core operating system security. Various aspects of the operating system have been modified to make it more difficult for applications to run without permission, as well as modifing files on the system without the users\' knowledge.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"well\">\r\n<h4>Network Control</h4>\r\nNetwork control over machine level detail via Group Policy Objects (GPO) has been vastly expanded. You can control more things, to a finer level of detail, than you could with either Windows XP or Windows Vista.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"well\">\r\n<h4>Complete Support</h4>\r\nMore complete and standard support for today\'s newer architecture machines. Multi-core and multi-socket machines are handled with a more advanced thread manager, allowing more performance to be achieved with existing hardware. Newer hardware takes this advantage even further with support for SSD/USB swap drives, virtualized component utilization and other features simply not available in Windows XP.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"well\">\r\n<h4>Windows Server Integration</h4>\r\nMore direct and tightly integrated control with Windows Server 2008/2011 SBS/2012. If you have a Windows Server 2003 architecture, your Windows 7 clients will work without issue. But if you have any of the next generation Windows Server products you\'ll find additional control and configuration options available on the Windows 7/8 machines that can aid in creating a more standardized and more easily managed IT infrastructure. From deployment options to product update managment, administering Windows 7/8 boxes is just easier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe invite you to read <a title=\"Ten Things You Should Know About Windows 7 vs. Windows XP\" href=\"http://www.novastar.net/gk-231015.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Ten Things You Should Know About Windows 7 vs. Windows XP</a> by Global Knowledge® to get a detailed analysis on the differences between Windows XP and Windows 7.\r\n\r\n</div>");
INSERT INTO wp_postmeta VALUES("667","162","_section_2","field_550ae597ee62b");
INSERT INTO wp_postmeta VALUES("668","162","section_3","<div class=\"row-fluid\">\r\n<div class=\"span12\">\r\n<div class=\"accordion-container\">\r\n<div class=\"row-fluid\">\r\n<h2 class=\"heading\">Situational Adapability</h2>\r\nIn the old days it was called \"disaster recovery\". The business world demands a much more dynamic approach to securing the Enterprise. Power will go out. ISPs will disrupt and/or discontinue service. Some times these events will last only minutes or hours - so the solutions must be flexible enough to kick in quickly (no day long tape restores) but also able to relinquish control when normalcy is restored (no list of manual changes to the corporate firewall to shift traffic back).\r\n<h3>Mail routing that allows continuity during several types of outages</h3>\r\n<ul class=\"pointer\">\r\n	<li>What is the main purpose of e-mail during an event? Who are the highest priority client set that needs to be addressed?</li>\r\n	<li>What is more important, missing inbound messages or being able to continue sending outbound messages?</li>\r\n	<li>Filter messages yourself, to lower monthly costs? External filter, to isolate and secure your mail server from the public Internet?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Multi-point access to data</h3>\r\n<ul class=\"pointer\">\r\n	<li>Any architecture with a single point of data availability failure is ripe for a downtime disruption.</li>\r\n	<li>Even with DFS and other technologies in place if they are all reliant upon the same data store then the failure point has merely been shifted, not eliminated.</li>\r\n	<li>Based upon your business needs, compliance obligations, budget, revisioning constraints and timeline for a restore in the event of data loss the best solution for you might not be a single solution.</li>\r\n	<li>Replication of data between locations vs. off-site backup? Off-site to the public cloud, a controlled 3rd party cloud, your own cloud or standard machines co-located at another facility?</li>\r\n	<li>We can help you architect a plan that meets your needs and also allows you to retain as much, or as little, possession over the stored data as you like.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Network convergence</h3>\r\n<ul class=\"pointer\">\r\n	<li>Wireless devices bridging onto your wired infrstructure can cause hassles if they are not controlled. Are you limiting what impact they have on your network or just waiting for it to become a problem?</li>\r\n	<li>The cost of high speed networking equipment has decreased substantially in the past few years, do you have redundant links on standby for your backbones?</li>\r\n	<li>Spare/redundant hardware in place in the switching layer?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you know what, and who, is taking the largest share of your network traffic - really?</li>\r\n	<li>Our testing and evaluations services can help you determine fault tolerant hardware solutions that add stabilty and minimize downtime.</li>\r\n	<li>Our analysis services can analyze your network and warn you of potential problems and help you troubleshoot throughput and latency issues that you\'re experiencing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>");
