INSERT INTO wp_posts VALUES("436","1","2014-12-21 13:11:26","2014-12-21 13:11:26","The buzz in the manufacturing world in general and prototyping in particular has surrounded the concept of 3D printing. Many in the industry are now adopting the term Additive Manufacturing for this process since it encompasses more than just one type of equipment. The term is also more accurate since it describes a production technique based on building from the bottom up rather than creating something from a piece of material.  Additive Manufacturing creates products by layering and allows the use of a wide range of different materials. The technology has opened up a wide range of possibilities in the manufacturing world, especially when it comes to prototyping. Things can be done now that weren’t possible even a year ago.\r\n\r\n<strong>Alternate Material Use</strong>\r\nOne of the biggest advantages in the process is the ability to use multiple types of material. In the past seven or eight months there’s been a huge breakthrough in the use of alternate materials. The metal area a year ago was extremely complex and inflexible and the parts that came out were functional but incredibly ugly and expensive. Turnaround time was glacially slow as well. Material options now extend from plastic, polymers and sub polymers to different organic materials. There is even more being done with edible materials where you can custom design and create cakes, as an example.\r\n\r\nWith Additive Manufacturing, you now have the possibility of in-house metal fabrication. You can take a plastic produced model from rapid prototyping and coat it in metal through a nano-level electrolysis process. You are able to extrude the metal tiny droplet by tiny droplet using an electro magnetic device with a depositing tip allowing you to build metal parts. You no longer have to do the billeting and bridgeporting with the carving out of the null matter. You literally build it up from the bottom.\r\n\r\nYou are also able to produce a mathematically improbable piece of metal since you are building it up layer by layer instead of having to get tools into unreachable corners. It’s now possible to produce hollowed out pieces as well.\r\n\r\n<strong>Multiple Color Options</strong>\r\nColor is another area where opportunities are exploding. Traditionally changing colors meant swapping out different spools on a one, two, or three-color machine. The latest units work more like an ink jet printer where it produces an off white polymer and the color is added by depositing it onto the strata. That opens the possibilities of 20+ million colors, on demand as the material is coming out of the extruder.\r\n\r\nThis also significantly reduces material costs. You no longer have to maintain a certain base amount of spools of a certain number of colors that can end up sitting on your shelf. Now you have several spools of a neutral material that you color as demand warrants. This allows you to better focus on customer demand and consumption for more efficient production and enhanced customer satisfaction.\r\n\r\nThis advanced process has proven to be a boon to the rapid prototype movement. Not only can you quickly produce prototypes in house, but you can unleash the creativity of your staff who are no longer limited by traditional technology.\r\n\r\nTaking advantage of Additive Manufacturing can help you become more responsive in the marketplace and increase your competitiveness. Have you used Additive Manufacturing? Is there an application for it in your business?","Additive Manufacturing Opens Exciting Opportunities","","publish","open","open","","additive-manufacturing-opens-exciting-opportunities","","","2015-04-13 14:37:06","2015-04-13 14:37:06","","0","http://novastar.dev/?p=436","0","post","","0");
