INSERT INTO wp_posts VALUES("438","1","2015-02-15 13:12:02","2015-02-15 13:12:02","Every company today is heavily focused on the bottom line. That makes sense in a uncertain economy where competition is fierce. For publicly traded companies, there’s the additional constant pressure from Wall Street to show positive short-term results.\r\n\r\nOne of the biggest victims of this cost containment attitude is the CapEx budget. The “here and now” or “immediate must-haves” normally find there way through, but it always seems to be a struggle getting funding for hardware or software purchases that fulfill longer term needs.\r\n\r\nSuch is the case when it comes to requests for up to date CAE/CAD software and equipment. Developers who use the technology on a regular basis understand the need to make such investments. Administrators facing difficult budget constraints, however, sometimes resist making what looks to them as simply an expense they’d rather avoid. The result in many cases is that design departments lack appropriate resources for developers to do their jobs.\r\n\r\nThus was born the practice of seat sharing, where a group of developers in a department share one or two machines to get their work done. While in theory this sounds like an efficient use of resources, in practice it can cause a number of problems for companies of any size. Here are four of them.\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Diverts Resources</strong>\r\nSharing one or two machines is clearly less costly than providing a workstation for each person in a department. But when calculating the cost/benefit of buying additional seats, some of the soft expenses can be left out of the equation. For example, with one workstation, someone has to coordinate how the resource will be shared. There will inevitably be times when more than one developer needs to use the station causing conflicts. The result is setting up and managing a schedule so everyone has equal access to the unit. That means turning high-priced developers into production schedulers – not the best use of valuable resources.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. Creates Bottlenecks</strong>\r\nThose unavoidable conflicts with multiple developers working on projects can also cause bottlenecks. For example, a developer doing a deformative model may need 28 minutes to run a simulation. If another developer shows up shortly thereafter needing the machine, he or she must wait until the process is complete. However the conflict is resolved, it means one or more developers will be at a standstill until they can get availability to a workstation. The downtime affects the overall schedule on a project since the developer can’t move on to the next stage until the bottleneck is resolved. In a just-in-time environment, these types of delays can have serious impact on the business.\r\n\r\n<strong>3. Productivity Loss</strong>\r\nIn some cases, developers will resolve conflicts by stopping their jobs to allow another person to have access to the seat. This not only stops the efficient flow of work, but it also can cause potential problems. Interrupting a job in process can result in jobs being accidently cancelled or crashing jobs running in the background. This causes rework creating another hidden cost that’s hard to measure or track.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Lowers Morale</strong>\r\nAnother way companies try to resolve these conflicts is by forcing developers to change shifts to spread out the demand on the system. Again this often seems like a reasonable solution to management, but asking people to work second and third shifts can cause resentment and a drop in morale. In a worst-case scenario, it can lead to the loss of talented developers who decide to change jobs rather than going to off-hour shifts.\r\n\r\nThere’s no question that businesses must be smart and creative when establishing their budgets. And while seat sharing may look like a reasonable alternative, when all the actual costs in productivity loss, rework, and lowered morale are taken into account, in reality, it might not be the best choice.","4 Disadvantages of Seat Sharing for CAD/CAE","","publish","open","open","","4-disadvantages-of-seat-sharing-for-cadcae","","","2015-04-13 14:37:24","2015-04-13 14:37:24","","0","http://novastar.dev/?p=438","0","post","","0");
INSERT INTO wp_posts VALUES("439","1","2015-04-01 13:12:02","2015-04-01 13:12:02","Every company today is heavily focused on the bottom line. That makes sense in a uncertain economy where competition is fierce. For publicly traded companies, there’s the additional constant pressure from Wall Street to show positive short-term results.\r\n\r\nOne of the biggest victims of this cost containment attitude is the CapEx budget. The “here and now” or “immediate must-haves” normally find there way through, but it always seems to be a struggle getting funding for hardware or software purchases that fulfill longer term needs.\r\n\r\nSuch is the case when it comes to requests for up to date CAE/CAD software and equipment. Developers who use the technology on a regular basis understand the need to make such investments. Administrators facing difficult budget constraints, however, sometimes resist making what looks to them as simply an expense they’d rather avoid. The result in many cases is that design departments lack appropriate resources for developers to do their jobs.\r\n\r\nThus was born the practice of seat sharing, where a group of developers in a department share one or two machines to get their work done. While in theory this sounds like an efficient use of resources, in practice it can cause a number of problems for companies of any size. Here are four of them.\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Diverts Resources</strong>\r\nSharing one or two machines is clearly less costly than providing a workstation for each person in a department. But when calculating the cost/benefit of buying additional seats, some of the soft expenses can be left out of the equation. For example, with one workstation, someone has to coordinate how the resource will be shared. There will inevitably be times when more than one developer needs to use the station causing conflicts. The result is setting up and managing a schedule so everyone has equal access to the unit. That means turning high-priced developers 