INSERT INTO wp_posts VALUES("442","1","2015-02-21 13:15:25","2015-02-21 13:15:25","The concept of sustainability and environmental friendliness continues to be a focus in the manufacturing world. It’s now commonly accepted that designing products with sustainability in mind is good for the environment, consumers, brands, and business in general.\r\n\r\nWhile many businesses are striving to comply with eco-design concepts as a show of corporate responsibility, growing government intervention makes the need more urgent. European Union legislation already makes such product design decisions mandatory and it won’t be long before other countries follow suit. Dealing with these requirements and the negative environmental impact of products after they are manufactured can be cumbersome and costly. It’s much more effective to build sustainability into the product at the design phase to prevent negative outcomes after they’re already on the market.\r\n\r\nTo meet this demand, it’s imperative that designers consider sustainability from the very beginning of the design stage. One way to implement this type of eco-design is through the use of Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) principles. LCA takes the entire product life cycle into consideration during design and includes raw material selection, manufacturing processes, product use, energy consumption, transportation, and end of life issues. By reviewing product design at this detailed level, LCA assists designers in assessing product development and ultimately helps them make eco-friendly decisions.\r\n\r\n<strong>LCA Challenges</strong>\r\nDespite being a powerful enabler in eco-design, integrating CAD/CAE with LCA presents challenges. The most serious is the fact that there’s a significant difference between the two disciplines. CAD is an iterative process while LCA is an evaluation technique.\r\n\r\nProduct specs and other data points continually evolve during the design phase so evaluating this moving target is difficult. LCA review therefore is not as effective in the early stages of design. It is most useful for the evaluation to be done as close to the finished design as possible. LCA is most beneficial when comparing options on specific decision points. That said, incorporating LCA into the design process remains a key factor in achieving sustainability.\r\n\r\n<strong>Integrating LCA Principles</strong>\r\nSustainable Brands, a learning, collaboration, and commerce community of over 348,000 sustainable business leaders from around the world, lists six requirements for integrating LCA principles into product design.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Initiate design with eco-design principles</li>\r\n	<li>Recognize iterative process of design</li>\r\n	<li>Allow designers to easily access and aggregate data about the impact of materials</li>\r\n	<li>Provide sufficient accuracy to make LCA information useful</li>\r\n	<li>Store collective design knowledge and make it universally available</li>\r\n	<li>Incorporate costs associated with alternate designs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMarrying LCA into the basic CAD/CAE design process isn’t easy but striving to do so is critical if we hope to reduce the environmental footprint of products that are being created.","Integrating LCA and CAD for Sustainable Product Design","","publish","open","open","","integrating-lca-and-cad-for-sustainable-product-design","","","2015-04-13 14:36:39","2015-04-13 14:36:39","","0","http://novastar.dev/?p=442","0","post","","0");
