INSERT INTO wp_posts VALUES("468","1","2015-04-01 18:46:14","2015-04-01 18:46:14","Producing innovative products in an on demand world requires flexibility. This is especially true in the design phase where significant time can be gained or lost before manufacturing even begins. One of the areas that is ripe for acceleration opportunities is in the prototyping process.\r\n\r\nTraditionally, models are designed and then prototyping is outsourced to a third party – many times one located overseas. This is not only time consuming, but can also be costly. As a result, more manufacturers today are turning to in-house, rapid prototyping as an alternative.\r\n\r\nHere are seven reasons you should consider the same approach.\r\n<h3>1. Faster turn time</h3>\r\nTraditional outsourcing usually takes a week or more because of transit time. But this is only part of the delay when a third party does the prototyping. A hidden lag time comes from the internal development process as well. Because of the time and expense involved, companies hesitate to send out for the prototype until they have something close to the finished model. With in-house prototyping, time and expense is less of an issue, so products can go to prototyping sooner. This can significantly reduce the time line for overall development.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. Reduced errors</strong>\r\nIn addition to speeding up development, more frequent prototyping can also reduce costly errors in the tooling process. You can be more confident that you have the most up to date design before creating costly dies or molds. This comes into play particularly when it comes to fit and finish.\r\n\r\nFor example when you have a flange going into a receptacle, getting the mold made and then doing a prototype in a limited production run can reveal that it may be a millimeter or two off. Making another mold to correct the problem is expensive so many times it isn’t done. With rapid prototyping you’re not making a mold every time you make a change so each prototype can contain multiple changes. You can make every change with every revision. This means you have reduced errors through iterative improvements and you don’t have to settle or compromise on your design changes.\r\n\r\n<strong>3. Productivity Gains</strong>\r\nPrototyping in house reduces the “lag time” when development is at a standstill waiting for prototypes to come back from the supplier. This time is virtually eliminated when it comes to the in house process resulting in a more productive, cost effective development team.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Cost Savings</strong>\r\nReduction in shipping costs helps offset the investment needed to buy the equipment. Every time you do it yourself, you’re increasing your savings by eliminating outsourcing. You also save by cutting out the vendor profit margin and the cost of transportation.\r\n\r\n<strong>5. Increased innovation</strong>\r\nWhen faced with the costs and time lags of outsourcing, you might hesitate to create multiple prototypes for a product and instead choose to focus on the most likely design. However with in-house, rapid prototyping, you’re able to produce multiple prototypes with varying features including several iterations of each. This means you can try out hundreds of options in the time it would take for your outsourced prototype to come back from the vendor. This encourages innovation and ensures that the final piece will be the most appropriate design for your project.\r\n\r\n<strong>6. Better Security</strong>\r\nControlling the prototyping process in house means you’re not sending valuable designs to a third party who may or may not have the same security protocols in place. Maintaining this control guards against piracy that can quickly undermine your entire product development effort.\r\n\r\n<strong>7. Future Proofing</strong>\r\nAdvances in prototyping technology have multiplied the number of things you can now do that were pipe dreams only a few years ago. You can now produce innovative designs in various materials and colors at a fraction of former costs. With in-house, rapid prototyping you can take advantage of this versatility to introduce exciting new products. And producing them in house eliminates time and cost issues related to outsourcing while keeping you at the forefront of the industry.\r\n\r\nThe transition to in-house, rapid prototyping is dramatically reducing the need for third party outsourcing and increasing the effectiveness of product development teams. How are you handling your prototyping process? Have you considered bringing the process in house?","7 Benefits of In-House vs. Outsourced Rapid Prototyping","","inherit","open","open","","433-revision-v1","","","2015-04-01 18:46:14","2015-04-01 18:46:14","","433","http://novastar.dev/433-revision-v1/","0","revision","","0");
